excerpt: This 600-acre coastal park offers boardwalks, lookout points, picnic sites with grills & more.
detail_description: Irving Nature Park, located just a 15-minute drive from downtown Saint John, covers 600 acres of coastal land along the Bay of Fundy. The park was established to protect 11 kilometers of shoreline and features six distinct ecosystems, including forests, mud flats, salt marshes, volcanic rock formations, and a sandy beach. Visitors can explore groomed trails and a gravel road for walking, hiking, and biking while enjoying picturesque views of the Fundy coastline.
name: Irving Nature Park
address: 1790 Sand Cove Rd, Saint John, NB E2M 4Z8, Canada

excerpt: Iconic city market dating to the 1870s with vendors carrying local produce, meats, seafood & crafts.
detail_description: The Saint John City Market, a historic landmark dating back to the 1870s, is a must-visit destination in Saint John. This iconic market offers an array of local produce, meats, seafood, and crafts from various vendors. Situated across from Kings Square and boasting a distinctive roof resembling a ship's hull, the market provides an excellent opportunity for visitors to explore and capture unique photos.
name: Saint John City Market
address: 47 Charlotte St, Saint John, NB E2L 2H8, Canada

excerpt: Tidal rapids on the Saint John River, popular for whitewater kayaking, with an observation deck.
detail_description: The Reversing Falls in Saint John, New Brunswick is a must-see attraction known for its tidal rapids on the Saint John River. It is popular for whitewater kayaking and features an observation deck for visitors to enjoy the natural phenomenon. The Bay of Fundy, home to the highest tides in the world, influences the flow of the river. At low tide, visitors can explore sea caves and rock formations along miles of dry land.
name: Reversing Falls
address: Saint John, NB E2M 3N6, Canada

excerpt: Sizable natural area with many trails & lakes for boating, swimming & fishing, plus winter skating.
detail_description: Rockwood Park is a sprawling natural area located near the Uptown area, offering a diverse mix of neighborhoods, shopping centers, and nature parks. Spanning over 2,200 acres, this central city park features an array of trails, lakes, and walking paths for various outdoor activities. It is a popular destination for locals and tourists alike throughout the year. The park is part of the UNESCO Stonehammer Geopark system due to its rich geological history spanning billions of years.
name: Rockwood Park
address: 10 Fisher Lakes Dr, Saint John, NB E2K 5S6, Canada

excerpt: Featuring a restored 1909 bandstand, this public space features gardens & several monuments.
detail_description: Kings Square, established in 1734 and named after King George III, is a historic public space in Saint John. It features a restored 1909 bandstand, gardens, statues of great Canadians and war heroes, and historical buildings like City Hall and Trinity Church. The square is a hub for arts, culture, and heritage with attractions such as the Imperial Theatre hosting various performances throughout the year and the Farmers Market offering local produce and handmade goods.
name: Kings Square
address: 100 King St, Saint John, NB E2L 1G4, Canada

detail_description: Imperial Theatre, a century-old historic building in Saint John, was originally built as a vaudeville house in 1913. Designed by architect Albert E. Westover, it has hosted renowned performers like John Philip Sousa and Ethel Barrymore. The theatre also has a Hollywood connection through local businessman Walter Golding, mentored by Louis B. Mayer of MGM Studios fame. Visitors praise the friendly staff and excellent customer service at the theatre's online box office.
name: Imperial Theatre
address: 12 King Square S, Saint John, NB E2L 5B8, Canada

excerpt: Site of defensive tower used from the War of 1812 till WWII, now offering exhibits & scenic climbs.
detail_description: Carleton Martello Tower National Historic Site, located in Saint John, was constructed in 1813 as a defensive fort to protect the port from potential attacks. It is one of the few surviving Canadian towers of its kind and served as headquarters for anti-aircraft defense during World War II. Today, it operates as a museum showcasing military life dating back to the 18th century and offers scenic views over Saint John.
name: Carleton Martello Tower National Historic Site
address: 454 Whipple St, Saint John, NB E2M 2R3, Canada

excerpt: Traditional 1817 Georgian home of a British Loyalist, with original period interiors & furniture.
detail_description: Loyalist House, a traditional 1817 Georgian home located in Saint John, is a significant piece of history. Built by Loyalist David Merritt between 1810 and 1817, it stands as the oldest wooden building in the area and survived the Great Fire. The house has been preserved with its original period interiors and furniture intact.
name: Loyalist House
address: 120 Union St, Saint John, NB E2L 1A3, Canada

detail_description: Market Square is a charming street that has preserved its historical ambiance, featuring restaurants and bars housed in 19th-century building facades. The area exudes an old-world charm while also embracing a modern and trendy atmosphere. Visitors can enjoy leisurely strolls along the North Market Wharfs waterfront boardwalk, where they may chance upon outdoor festivals and live music events held on the stage.
name: Market Square
address: Saint John, NB, Canada

excerpt: Displays about the province's history, science & art, including the popular Hall of Great Whales.
detail_description: The New Brunswick Museum is a treasure trove of the province's rich history, science, and art. Although it may be temporarily closed as it seeks a new location, this museum offers an array of fascinating exhibits that cater to visitors of all ages. One highlight is the Hall of Great Whales, which captivates children and adults alike.
name: New Brunswick Museum
address: 277 Douglas Ave, Saint John, NB E2K 1E5, Canada

detail_description: Fort Howe National Historic Site, located in Saint John, New Brunswick, is a designated national historic site that dates back to 1777. Built by the British during the American Revolutionary War, it served as a defense against American rebels and provided protection to surrounding settlements until the end of the War of 1812. Positioned on a towering rock, it offers unparalleled views of the harbor and up the river.
name: Fort Howe National Historic Site
address: Magazine St, Saint John, NB E2K 2S4, Canada

excerpt: A homey dining room with bar seating featuring pasta, classic Italian dishes, desserts & wines.
detail_description: Italian by Night is a charming restaurant located in the heart of Saint John's uptown area. During the day, it transforms into Urban Deli, reflecting its rich history. The menu offers classic Italian dishes with a modern twist and an extensive wine selection. Guests can enjoy handmade pasta and culturally diverse sandwiches in a cozy dining room or on the popular outdoor patio during warmer months.
name: Italian by Night
address: 97 Germain St, Saint John, NB E2L 2E5, Canada

detail_description: Moosehead Breweries Ltd., located in Saint John, New Brunswick, has a rich history dating back to 1867 when Susannah Oland began brewing her October Brown Ale. Over the years, Moosehead has become one of the most popular breweries in New Brunswick, offering behind-the-scenes tours that showcase their time-honored brewing practices and allow visitors to explore the brew-house while sampling a variety of their popular brews.
name: Moosehead Breweries Ltd.
address: 89 Main St W, Saint John, NB E2M 3N3, Canada

excerpt: Saint John is a city on the Bay of Fundy, in New Brunswick, Canada. It’s known for the Reversing Rapids, a phenomenon caused by bay tides colliding with the Saint John River. Food and craft stalls fill the Saint John City Market, in an 1876 building. On a peninsula nearby, trails wind through Irving Nature Park’s salt marshes, volcanic rock and forests. The 1913 Imperial Theatre stages plays, concerts and dance.
detail_description: Saint John, located in New Brunswick, Canada, is a city known for its natural wonders and cultural attractions. The Reversing Rapids phenomenon at the Bay of Fundy and the historic Saint John City Market are popular tourist spots. The province itself boasts dense forests, marshlands, and rolling hills with a multicultural population speaking English and French. With its highest tides in the world, rugged coastline, pristine beaches, and ample fishing waters, New Brunswick offers untouched wilderness for outdoor enthusiasts.
name: Saint John
address: New Brunswick, Canada

detail_description: Market Square is a charming destination offering a unique shopping experience with its local boutiques, clothing shops, home decor stores, and handmade jewelry outlets. The variety of restaurants cater to different tastes, serving everything from Belgian waffles to Mexican cuisine. This beautiful place is perfect for year-round visits and provides indoor warmth during the winter months. In addition to shopping opportunities, Market Square features entertainment options such as swimming and hockey at Brunswick Square.
name: Market Square
address: 1 Market Square, Saint John, NB E2L 4Z6, Canada

excerpt: High-end, family-owned place since 2006 with a hip vibe providing Asian fusion plates & local beers.
detail_description: Thandi is a high-end, family-owned restaurant with a hip vibe that has been serving delicious Asian fusion dishes and local beers since 2006. The menu offers a tantalizing fusion of East and West flavors, featuring steaks, seafood, chicken, and authentic Indian curries prepared with great care and attention to detail. This popular restaurant is known for its amazing mosaic of flavors that combine the best of Eastern and Western cuisines.
name: Thandi
address: 33 Canterbury St, Saint John, NB E2L 2C6, Canada

excerpt: Hip hangout with late hours offering inventive, seasonal eats, local craft beers & an outdoor patio.
detail_description: Saint John Ale House is a trendy spot with a late-night scene, serving up creative seasonal dishes and local craft beers. It's the perfect place to unwind after a day of exploring the city, offering an outdoor patio for enjoying local brews like Tool Shed Porter. The menu features succulent scallops wrapped in crispy bacon with maple syrup, as well as massive lobster rolls that are not to be missed.
name: Saint John Ale House
address: 1 Market Square, Saint John, NB E2L 4Z6, Canada

detail_description: Discover the vibrant and trendy AREA 506 Waterfront Container Village in Saint John, a unique attraction located right by the waterfront. This creative hub is made up of over 60 colorful shipping containers housing an array of retail shops, a performance space, a waterfront container bar, food trucks, public art installations, and pop-up activities. It's not just a shopping destination but also serves as a platform for local vendors and artisans to showcase their talents.
name: AREA 506 Waterfront Container Village
address: 85 Water St, Saint John, NB E2L 5G1, Canada

detail_description: When visiting Prince William St, be sure to explore the renowned City Market with its distinctive roof resembling an inverted ship's hull. Take a leisurely stroll along Prince William Street, which is celebrated for hosting the most uninterrupted array of Italianate and 2nd Empire architecture in Canada.
name: Prince William St
address: Saint John, NB, Canada

detail_description: In Saint John, a vibrant city with an emerging artsy scene, visitors can experience the iconic Reversing Falls. This natural wonder is known for its unique phenomenon of waterfalls that reverse their flow. It's recommended to time your visit just before low tide to witness the water changing direction. The journey to Reversing Falls may involve a long walk, but the beautiful scenery and opportunity to observe seals near the viewing platform make it worthwhile.
name: Reversing Falls
address: 100 Fallsview Ave, Saint John, NB E2K 0G8, Canada

excerpt: Paved harbourside promenade offering walking & cycling paths & scenic views.
detail_description: Harbour Passage is a picturesque harbourside promenade with walking and cycling paths, offering scenic views of the Bay of Fundy. The cranberry-colored trail connects the Reversing Falls Rapids to uptown Saint John, featuring interconnected walkways, lookouts, and heritage sites. Visitors can enjoy walking, running, or biking along this beautiful route.
name: Harbour Passage
address: 1 Market Square, Saint John, NB E2L 0A1, Canada

detail_description: The Saint John Jewish Historical Museum offers a fascinating look into the history and culture of the city's Jewish community. The museum houses various artifacts and photographs that trace the stories of individuals and families who immigrated to Canada. Visitors can expect a guided tour, although some suggest starting with a historical video for better context. The museum is praised for its friendly and knowledgeable staff, making it an incredible attraction in Saint John.
name: Saint John Jewish Historical Museum
address: 91 Leinster St, Saint John, NB E2L 1J2, Canada

name: Cathedral of the Immaculate Conception
address: 91 Waterloo St, Saint John, NB E2L 3P9, Canada

excerpt: Funky, volunteer-run repository for information & history of the local police force.
detail_description: Nestled in the heart of Saint John, the Saint John Police Museum is a charming and quirky destination that offers a fascinating glimpse into the history of one of Canada's oldest police forces. This volunteer-run museum showcases an array of artifacts, including a vintage 1965 Volkswagen traffic car that's perfect for photo ops. Visitors can engage with retired police officers who share captivating stories from their careers, making it an enriching experience.
name: Saint John Police Museum
address: 56 Prince William St, Saint John, NB E2L 2B1, Canada

detail_description: If you're looking for a vibrant spot to enjoy some entertainment, TD Station is the place to be! This venue hosts thrilling Saint John Sea Dogs hockey games, so make sure to check their schedule and grab your tickets in advance. Beyond sports, you can also visit the Family Entertainment Centre for an exciting evening filled with bowling, bumper cars, and arcade fun.
name: TD Station
address: 99 Station St, Saint John, NB E2L 4X4, Canada

detail_description: Handworks Gallery offers a diverse range of art forms, providing a vibrant display of color and beauty. This gallery showcases both modern and classic styles of painting, as well as unique jewelry and wood crafts. The selection caters to various budgets, making it an ideal place for finding gifts or mementos. The owner is knowledgeable about the represented artists and offers helpful advice during tours.
name: Handworks Gallery
address: 12 King St, Saint John, NB E2L 4S7, Canada

detail_description: Stone Church is a historic and spiritually vibrant congregation located in the heart of Saint John. The church offers a welcoming atmosphere, with friendly and kind people. It hosts various events, including a great Bible study on Saturdays that used to include meals. The interior boasts a rustic oak decor that has aged beautifully. Additionally, it provides a relaxing space for the community to gather over snacks and beverages. This architectural marvel is also an excellent spot for photographers due to its unique and dark style that sparks curiosity and wonder.
name: Stone Church
address: 87 Carleton St, Saint John, NB E2L 2Z2, Canada

detail_description: Nestled just a short drive from St. John, Mispec Beach is a hidden gem that offers visitors a serene escape with its fine-grained sand and stunning views of the Bay of Fundy. Once a recreational spot for World War II servicemen, this beach now features free parking, restrooms, and even a playground for children. The landscape is uniquely Canadian, where fir trees replace palm trees and the vibrant waters invite adventurous souls willing to brave the chill without wetsuits.
name: Mispec Beach
address: Simonds Parish, NB E2J 4W7, Canada

excerpt: Riverfront area with views of the reversing rapids, statues of historic locals & picnic tables.
detail_description: Wolastoq Park is a riverfront area that offers stunning views of the reversing rapids and the city of Saint John. The park showcases engraved wooden statues that depict important local historical figures along a gravel path. It is an ideal place for leisurely walks, both in the morning and evening. The park provides numerous benches where visitors can enjoy picnics while admiring the picturesque surroundings. Wolastoq Park was established in 2004 by J.D.
name: Wolastoq Park
address: 211 Lancaster Ave, Saint John, NB E2M 2K8, Canada

detail_description: The Old No.2 Engine House Museum is a provincial heritage site in Saint John, built in 1840-41 and designed by architect John Cunningham. It serves as a museum and exhibit hall showcasing the history of firefighting in the city, including a special exhibit on the Great Fire of 1877. Visitors can explore historic equipment, photographs, and other artifacts while learning about the department's history from knowledgeable staff.
name: Old No.2 Engine House Museum
address: 24 Sydney St, Saint John, NB E2L 2L3, Canada

detail_description: Cape Spencer Lighthouse, located just a short drive from the city, offers phenomenal views of the Bay of Fundy from high cliffs. The lighthouse stands proudly on a steep hill, providing breathtaking scenery. However, visitors have expressed disappointment over the ugly graffiti on the lighthouse. Despite this, it remains a popular spot for locals and tourists alike. The area features unobstructed cliff drops and various hiking trails such as the Waltons trail.
name: Cape Spencer Lighthouse
address: 3513 Red Head Rd, Mispec, NB E2S 1Y1, Canada

detail_description: Nestled in the heart of Saint John, the Saint John Arts Centre is a vibrant cultural destination that invites visitors to immerse themselves in creativity. This former Carnegie library has been transformed into an extraordinary arts hub featuring five free public galleries showcasing captivating artwork from local and regional artists. Whether you're interested in attending engaging art exhibitions or participating in hands-on workshops, there's something for everyone at this dynamic center.
name: Saint John Arts Centre
address: 20 Peel Plaza, Saint John, NB E2L 3G6, Canada

detail_description: Little River Reservoir Park is a delightful location for various recreational activities such as swimming, walking, and allowing your canine companion to socialize at the dog park. The park has been rejuvenated and has become an excellent addition to the East Saint John lifestyle. It offers an array of amenities including a playground for children, scenic trails that encircle the picturesque lake, a sandy beach for relaxation, ample parking facilities, and even a captivating waterfall.
name: Little River Reservoir Park
address: 27 Pipe Line Rd E #23, Saint John, NB E2N 0E6, Canada

detail_description: Musquash Head Lighthouse, located in the St John area, has recently been repainted and is considered one of the most stunning and easily accessible lighthouses in the region. Visitors can reach it via a dirt road near the power station, which is manageable for most small sedans. The lighthouse offers breathtaking views of the Bay and rugged coastline. It can be accessed through various hiking trails or by driving to specific points.
name: Musquash Head Lighthouse
address: Saint John, NB E2M 7K8, Canada

detail_description: In the last couple of years, with the world becoming more interconnected, there has been a growing appreciation for the things that turn a house into a home. Trinity Galleries, an art establishment in Saint John for over 25 years, has played a significant role in enhancing living spaces. This exceptional institution is not to be missed by any art enthusiast or collector due to its stunning collection of artwork. The owner, Beth McGloan, is both generous and knowledgeable, making the visit even more worthwhile.
name: Trinity Galleries
address: 128 Germain St, Saint John, NB E2L 2E7, Canada

detail_description: Blueberry Hill Nature Preserve is a 19.8-hectare undeveloped property located on the easterly shoreline of St. John River. The trail offers a beautiful walk with opportunities to spot various animal and plant species. It is a great day hike, fairly easy to walk, and not stroller-friendly. The trail features benches and a lookout along the water where boats can be seen, making it an ideal spot for a quick hike in nature.
name: Blueberry Hill Nature Preserve
address: 76 Vair's Cove Rd, Saint John, NB E2M 0H3, Canada

detail_description: The Cobalt Art Gallery is a highly regarded establishment that receives praise for its impressive collection of artwork and helpful staff. Located in Fredericton, this gallery acts as a valuable resource for information on New Brunswick artists. Known for showcasing the best of Canadian art, it boasts an extensive assortment of Inuit carvings, antiques, and a diverse selection of persona carpets.
name: Cobalt Art Gallery
address: 111 Prince William St, Saint John, NB E2L 2B2, Canada

detail_description: The Three Sisters Lamp is a historic landmark located near Prince William St. in Saint John Harbour. These three red gas lamps were used by sea captains to navigate safely into the harbor at night, visible up to three miles out to sea. Restored in 1967 and replaced in 1997, these lamps have been guiding mariners since 1848. Visitors can enjoy the view of the Bay of Fundy and watch ships coming and going from this picturesque spot with a rich maritime history.
name: Three Sisters Lamp
address: Prince William St, Saint John, NB E2L 2C1, Canada

name: Swift Point [Green Head] Lighthouse
address: Saint John, NB E2K 4X4, Canada

name: Portal Sculpture by Phil Savage
address: 15 Market Square, Saint John, NB E2L 1E8, Canada

detail_description: Nestled in Moncton, the Musée acadien de l'Université de Moncton is a treasure trove for anyone eager to delve into Acadian culture and history. With over 42,000 artifacts and photographs showcased in its permanent exhibition titled "L'Aventure Acadienne," this museum offers an immersive experience that spans daily life, politics, and cultural heritage of the Acadian people. Visitors can also enjoy rotating temporary exhibits that broaden the narrative to include global historical themes.
name: Musée acadien de l'Université de Moncton
address: Pavillon Clément-Cormier, 405 Université Ave, Moncton, NB E1G 6G4, Canada

name: Sand Point Lighthouse
address: 4 Old Path Ln, Bayswater, NB E5S 1N4 Old Path Ln, Bayswater, NB E5S 1N4, Canada

detail_description: Kiwanis Play Park is a delightful destination for families, nestled within the scenic Rockwood Park. This well-maintained playground caters to children of all ages and offers a variety of engaging equipment that keeps little ones entertained for hours. The park is securely fenced and conveniently located next to horse stables, allowing kids to interact with friendly horses while they play. Parents can relax on ample benches as their children explore the safe toys and enjoy the inclusive features designed for all abilities.
name: Kiwanis Play Park
address: 175 Fisher Lakes Dr, Saint John, NB E2K 5S6, Canada

detail_description: Riverview Memorial Park is located next to the historic Collections and Research Centre on Douglas Avenue in Saint John. The park offers a peaceful atmosphere for visitors to relax, have conversations, and enjoy the surroundings. It is adjacent to the New Brunswick Museum building and provides a pleasant spot for leisure activities. Additionally, it features a convenient location near various amenities and serves as a gathering place for community events.
name: Riverview Memorial Park
address: 297 Douglas Ave #277, Saint John, NB E2K 1E5, Canada

name: Third Space
address: 87 Prince William St Suite 201, Saint John, NB E2L 2B2, Canada
